# CSS Nesting with &

Use the `&` parent selector to nest related styles. This keeps selectors grouped and reduces repetition.

## Examples

```css
/* ❌ BAD - flat, repetitive */
.button {
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;
}
.button:hover {
  background: #333;
}
.button.active {
  box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px #444;
}
.button.secondary {
  background: #222;
}
.button.secondary:hover {
  background: #333;
}

/* ✅ GOOD - nested with & */
.button {
  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;

  &:hover {
    background: #333;
  }

  &.active {
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px #444;
  }

  &.secondary {
    background: #222;

    &:hover {
      background: #333;
    }
  }
}
```

## Guidelines

- Nest pseudo-classes (`:hover`, `:focus`, `:disabled`) under their parent with `&`
- Nest modifier classes (`.active`, `.secondary`) with `&.modifier`
- Nest descendant selectors when they only apply in that context
- Keep nesting shallow (2–3 levels max) to avoid deep specificity
